markdown.markdownText:
**AWS ALB**
![Arch_Elastic-Load-Balancing_64.png](https://icon.icepanel.io/AWS/svg/Networking-Content-Delivery/Elastic-Load-Balancing.svg) 
Elastic Load Balancing automatically distributes your incoming traffic across multiple targets, such as EC2 instances, containers, and IP addresses, in one or more Availability Zones. It monitors the health of its registered targets and routes traffic only to the healthy targets. You can select the type of load balancer that best suits your needs. 

**Details of integrations to bring in AWS ALB metrics -** [amazon-alb](https://coralogix.com/docs/cloudwatch-metricstreams-kinesis-data-firehose/)

**Use Cases Covered**

* ALB availability % 
* ALB Request count trends
* Target Connection error trends by Application
* Response Time trends
* Healthy, Unhealthy host
* Healthy, Unhealthy DNS
* Consumed LCUs
* New Connections, Active Connections

More details can be found [here](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/application/load-balancer-cloudwatch-metrics.html#load-balancer-metrics-alb=)

resources.name: AWS Aurora
resources.description: View of key metrics relating to the health and performance of Amazon Aurora.

markdown.markdownText:
**Amazon Aurora**
![AWS Aurora](https://icon.icepanel.io/AWS/svg/Database/Aurora.svg)
Amazon Aurora (Aurora) is a fully managed relational database engine that's compatible with MySQL and PostgreSQL. You already know how MySQL and PostgreSQL combine the speed and reliability of high-end commercial databases with the simplicity and cost-effectiveness of open-source databases. 
Aurora includes a high-performance storage subsystem. Its MySQL- and PostgreSQL-compatible database engines are customized to take advantage of that fast distributed storage. The underlying storage grows automatically as needed 

This dashboard is part of the out-of-box Amazon Aurora extension and provides visibility to and alerting on key performance metrics.

**Use Cases Covered**

* Aurora Global DB Data Transfer Bytes (the amount of redo log data transferred from the source AWS Region to a secondary AWS Region)
* Aurora Global DB Progress Lag (the measure of how far the secondary cluster is behind the primary cluster for both user transactions and system transactions)
* Aurora Global DB Replication Lag (the amount of lag when replicating updates from the primary AWS Region)
* Aurora Global DB RPO (Recovery Point Objective) Lag (measures how far the secondary cluster is behind the primary cluster for user transactions)
* Backup Retention Period Storage Used (amount of backup storage used to support the point-in-time restore feature within the Aurora DB cluster's backup retention window)
* Serverless Database Capacity (current capacity of an Aurora Serverless DB cluster)
* Volume Bytes Used (amount of storage used by your Aurora DB cluster)
* Volume Read IOPS (number of billed read I/O operations from a cluster volume within a 5-minute interval)
* Volume Write IOPS (number of write disk I/O operations to the cluster volume, reported at 5-minute intervals)
* Aborted Clients (number of client connections that have not been closed properly)
* Active Transactions (average number of current transactions executing on an Aurora database instance per second)
* Aurora Memory Health State (indicates the memory health state. A value of 0 equals NORMAL. A value of 10 equals RESERVED)
* Aurora Memory Num Declined Sql Total (total number of queries declined as part of out-of-memory (OOM) avoidance)
* Aurora Replica Lag (the amount of lag when replicating updates from the primary instance)
* Aurora Slow Connection Handle Count (number of connections that have waited two seconds or longer to start the handshake)
* Aurora Memory Num Kill Query Total (total number of queries ended as part of OOM avoidance)

    More about performance monitoring of Amazon Aurora [here](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/apigateway/latest/developerguide/api-gateway-metrics-and-dimensions.html).

resources.name: AWS DynamoDB
resources.description: View and monitor the primary metrics of DynamoDB

markdown.markdownText: ![dynamoDB](https://icon.icepanel.io/AWS/svg/Database/DynamoDB.svg) Amazon DynamoDB is a fast, flexible and fully managed non-relational database service for any scale. DynamoDB enables customers to offload the administrative burdens of operating and scaling distributed databases to AWS so that they do not have to worry about hardware provisioning, setup and configuration, throughput capacity planning, replication, software patching or cluster scaling. This dashboard is part of the out-of-box Amazon DynamoDB extension and provides visibility to and alerting on key performance metrics. **Details of integrations to bring in Amazon DynamoDB logs -** [here](https://coralogix.com/docs/cloudwatch-metricstreams-kinesis-data-firehose/)

**Use Cases Covered**

* Successful Request Latency (The latency of successful requests to DynamoDB or DynamoDB Streams during the specified time period)
* Write Throttled Requests (Requests to DynamoDB that exceed the provisioned Write capacity units for a table or a global secondary index)
* Read Throttled Requests (Requests to DynamoDB that exceed the provisioned Read capacity units for a table or a global secondary index)
* Pending Replication Count (The number of item updates that are written to one replica table, but that have not yet been written to another replica in the global table)
* Replication Latency (The elapsed time between an updated item appearing in the DynamoDB stream for one replica table, and that item appearing in another replica in the global table)
* % of Provisioned Read/Write Capacity Consumed (The number of Read/Write capacity units consumed over the specified time period for both provisioned and on-demand capacity)
* System Errors (The requests to DynamoDB or DynamoDB Streams that generate an HTTP 500 status code during the specified time period)
* User Errors (Requests to DynamoDB or DynamoDB Streams that generate an HTTP 400 status code during the specified time period)
* Transaction Conflict (Rejected item-level requests due to transactional conflicts between concurrent requests on the same items)
* Returned Bytes (The number of bytes returned by GetRecords operations during the specified time period)
* Returned Records (The number of stream records returned by GetRecords operations during the specified time period)
* Returned Items (The number of items returned by Query, Scan or ExecuteStatement [Select] operations during the specified time period)

More about performance monitoring of Amazon DynamoDB[ here](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/amazondynamodb/latest/developerguide/metrics-dimensions.html)

markdown.markdownText:
**Amazon ElastiCache**
![Amazon ElastiCache](https://icon.icepanel.io/AWS/svg/Database/ElastiCache.svg) 
Amazon ElastiCache makes it easy to set up, manage and scale distributed in-memory cache environments in the AWS Cloud. It provides a high performance, resizable, and cost-effective in-memory cache, while removing complexity associated with deploying and managing a distributed cache environment.
You can operate Amazon ElastiCache in two formats. You can get started with a serverless cache or choose to design your own cache cluster. 

**Details of integrations to bring in Amazon ElastiCache metrics -** [Amazon-ElastiCache](https://coralogix.com/docs/cloudwatch-metricstreams-kinesis-data-firehose/)

**Use Cases Covered**

* Serverless cache metrics
* Host-Level Metrics
* Metrics for Memcached

To manage your cache, it's important that you know how your caches are performing. 
**More about performance monitoring of Amazon ElastiCache** [here](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonElastiCache/latest/mem-ug/MonitoringECMetrics.html)

markdown.markdownText:
**Confluent Kafka**
**Confluent Kafka** is an enterprise-ready data streaming platform built on Apache Kafka, designed for real-time data processing at scale. It extends Kafka with advanced capabilities for security, governance, and integrations across cloud and hybrid environments. Confluent Kafka provides three main functions: * **Publish and subscribe** to real-time data streams across applications and services. * **Store and manage** data streams durably with features like tiered storage and schema registry. * **Process and analyze** data streams in motion using ksqlDB and Kafka Streams. **More about performance monitoring of Confluent Kafka [here](https://api.telemetry.confluent.cloud/docs/descriptors/datasets/cloud)**

**Usecases Covered:**

* Track data volume and throughput per client and topic
* Monitor error rates, retries, and delivery reliability
* Evaluate batching and compression efficiency
* Measure request and response rates, sizes, and latency
* Monitor commit and rebalance activity and performance
* Check authentication and connection health
* Assess I/O processing efficiency and buffer memory usage
* Identify consumer lag, poll delays, and idle behavior
* Analyze fetch performance and responsiveness
* Detect unresponsive or unstable consumer group members
* Monitor network usage and detect broker-side throttling

More about performance monitoring of Kafka [here](https://api.telemetry.confluent.cloud/docs/descriptors/datasets/cloud)

markdown.markdownText:
****Elasticsearch**
![Elasticsearch](https://images.peerspot.com/image/upload/c_scale,f_auto,q_auto,w_100/y7VMVYQi1roWNxHRydsmTi38.png)
 
Elastisearch makes it easy to set up, manage and scale distributed in-memory cache environments in the AWS Cloud. It provides a high performance, resizable, and cost-effective in-memory cache, while removing complexity associated with deploying and managing a distributed cache environment.
You can operate Amazon ElastiCache in two formats. You can get started with a serverless cache or choose to design your own cache cluster. 

**Details of integrations to bring in Elasticsearch metrics -** [Elasticsearch](https://github.com/prometheus-community/elasticsearch_exporter)**

Observability Scenarios

 * KPI -  Key performance indicators summarising overall cluster and node health.
 * Cluster Health -  Status of the Elasticsearch cluster, reflecting node availability and shard allocation.
 * JVM Stats -  Metrics related to the Java Virtual Machine's memory usage and garbage collection.
 * Translog -  Statistics on transaction logs, tracking index operations and durability.
 * Breakers -  Monitoring of circuit breakers to prevent memory overuse in Elasticsearch operations.
 * OS Resource Utilisation -  Metrics on CPU, memory, and disk usage at the operating system level.
 * Documents -  Total number and size of documents stored across all indices.
 * Thread Pool -  Status of thread pools used for processing different tasks like search and indexing.
 * Caches -  Cache statistics, showing efficiency and hit rates for query and filter caching.
 * Segments -  Number and size of index segments, critical for search performance.
 * Indices -  Segments -  Detailed view of segment usage within individual indices for fine-grained analysis. 
**More about performance monitoring of  Elasticsearch** [here](https://github.com/prometheus-community/elasticsearch_exporter)

Mapping exceptions happen when we see the same field with two different types. For instance, in a log received from your account we see a field as type string and in another log the same field has been received as a number or a different type.
Mapping problems that are caused by the above conditions will result in a possibility to search the logs only in free text query. Logs that will have mapping exceptions in them or logs that contain fields that were not indexed due to the maximum set in your account will lack the advanced capabilities of Coralogix logs tab such as visualization of fields or advanced queries.

3. Exporters: Evaluate data delivery (sent records, failures, queue size).
4. System Stats: Monitor resource usage (CPU, memory, network, filesystem).

widgets.title: Traces Dropped Too Early
widgets.description: Number of Traces Dropped per second, before policy evaluation due to circular buffer overflow

markdown.markdownText:
# Tail Sampling Circular buffer

A circular buffer is used to ensure the number of traces in-memory doesn't exceed `num_traces`.

When a new trace arrives, the oldest trace is removed. 
This can cause a trace to be dropped before tail sampling policy is evaluated. 

To reduce the chance of this happening, increase `num_traces` or decrease `decision_wait`. Both of those options increase memory usage.

# Tail Sampling Policy Evaluation
**Policy Evaluation Errors** - indicate misconfigured Tail Sampling policy, check the Collector logs for more information.

**Policy Evaluation latency** measures sampling a batch of traces and passing sampled traces through the remainder of the collector pipeline.

 A latency exceeding **1 second** can delay sampling decisions beyond `decision_wait`, increasing the chance of traces being dropped before sampling.

widgets.title: message + message_str + msg field count by application & subsystem

dataprimeQuery.text:
source logs
| move msg to message
| filter $p.Application == null || $p.Application.arrayContains($l.applicationname)
| filter $p.Subsystem == null || $p.Subsystem.arrayContains($l.subsystemname)
| filter $m.severity.in(ERROR,WARNING,CRITICAL)
| filter message != null
| redact message /[0-9]+/ to ''
| groupby message, $l.applicationname, $l.subsystemname agg count() as message_count
| choose message, message_count, applicationname, subsystemname
| orderby message_count desc

| union (
    source logs
    | filter $p.Application == null || $p.Application.arrayContains($l.applicationname)
    | filter $p.Subsystem == null || $p.Subsystem.arrayContains($l.subsystemname)
    | lucene '_exists_:message AND _exists_:trace_id AND ("ERROR")'
    | filter 
        !message.matches(/"timestamp":"\d{13}"/) &&
        !message.matches(/^[0-9].*/) &&
        !message.matches(/^[{"].*/)
    | groupby message, $l.applicationname, $l.subsystemname agg count() as message_count
    | orderby message_count desc
    | filter message != null
    | choose message, message_count, applicationname, subsystemname
)

| union (
    source logs
    | move message_str to message
    | filter $p.Application == null || $p.Application.arrayContains($l.applicationname)
    | filter $p.Subsystem == null || $p.Subsystem.arrayContains($l.subsystemname)
    | filter $m.severity.in(ERROR,WARNING,CRITICAL)
    | lucene '_exists_:message'
    | groupby message, $l.applicationname, $l.subsystemname agg count() as message_count
    | choose message, message_count, applicationname, subsystemname
    | orderby message_count desc
) | filter $p.message == null || contains(message, $p.message)
